    "note": "Measured on a shared x86-64 Linux cloud container (release karac from kara main), NOT the corpus's Apple M5 Pro. Absolute times/sizes/RSS are NOT comparable to the sibling results.json; only within-file cross-language ratios are the signal. SEQ lane (KARAC_AUTO_PAR=0, single-threaded, fastest first): rust 298ms < rust_ovf 303ms < kara 591ms < c 650ms < go 802ms. Kara's seq codegen is ~2x behind rust -O but AHEAD of C and Go: this workload sorts each anchor's slope keys, and C's qsort / Go's sort.Slice pay an indirect-call (non-inlined) comparator tax while rust's sort_unstable and kara's Vec.sort inline theirs \u2014 so rust leads and kara sits between rust and C. AUTO-PAR lane (default build): kara 152ms \u2014 the independent-anchor outer loop is embarrassingly parallel and auto-parallelizes with ZERO source annotation, a 3.9x wall-clock speedup over kara-seq that beats even single-threaded rust -O by ~1.95x (and C by 4.3x, Go by 5.3x) on 4 cores. All lanes agree on the sink (696); correctness verified across interp/JIT/AOT and run==build==auto-par. Python (own timing, not cross-checked) shown for scale only. Re-run bench.sh on the M5 to refresh the canonical results.json table."
